I don&#39;t think Nihonto is particularly on the NRA&#39;s radar specifically.  But it is the same issue fundamentally, the private possession of arms, whether the particular arms under consideration consist of the Pennsylvania farmer&#39;s hunting rifle, or the SF Bay area tech mogul&#39;s Ichimonji daito.  My point was that the most effective lobbying organization on the basic issue is the National Rifle Association, whose membership typically runs between three and four million, and whose membership is well know to turn out and vote.  

If the NRA loses the fight over so-called assault weapons, then they will come after handguns.  If we lose on handguns, then they will go after rifles and shotguns.  And when all the firearms are on the prohibited list, as in Australia, swords, including Nihonto, will be added.   Those who collect antique arms would be well advised to participate in the fight now while they still have a large enough general constituency of hunters, target shooters, and ordinary firearms owners on the same side to constitute a constituency capable of making an electoral impact, and really influencing the politics of the situation.

I don&#39;t imagine that the NRA&#39;s organizational leadership is very conscious of the Nihonto collecting community at the present time, but I&#39;m sure the NRA philosophically regards the right to own and collect Nihonto as part of the same general right to keep and bear arms it devotes most of its energy and resources toward defending.  If American Nihonto organizations were inclined to work with the NRA on Second Amendment issues, I&#39;m sure that the NRA would welcome their assistance.

I don&#39;t know the inside story, but I seem to recall that the NRA was involved in publishing Man at Arms, the general arms collecting magazine, recently for some period of time, presumably to keep that journal afloat.  A feature on Japanese swords might not fit in terribly well in the American Rifleman, but would certainly be entirely appropriate to Man at Arms.  





